    "code": "E11.00",
    "rawCode": "E1100",
    "shortDesc": "Type 2 diab w hyprosm w/o nonket hyprgly-hypros coma (NKHHC)",
    "longDesc": "Type 2 diabetes mellitus with hyperosmolarity without nonketotic hyperglycemic-hyperosmolar coma (NKHHC)",
    "plainEnglish": "Type 2 diabetes is a condition where your body can't properly use or produce enough insulin, a hormone that controls blood sugar levels. Hyperosmolarity means your blood has become very concentrated with too much sugar and not enough water, making it thicker and more concentrated than normal. This code indicates the patient has this serious blood concentration problem but has NOT yet developed a life-threatening coma, though it's a warning sign that needs immediate medical attention.",
    "whoUses": "Endocrinologists, internists, and emergency medicine physicians use this code when treating hospitalized or acutely ill type 2 diabetic patients with severe dehydration and dangerously high blood sugar levels. This code frequently appears on hospital bills and EOB statements because it indicates a serious complication requiring intensive monitoring and IV fluids, making it a significant billing marker for diabetic emergencies.",
