    "longDesc": "Hypo-osmolality and hyponatremia",
    "plainEnglish": "Hyponatremia means you have too little sodium (salt) in your blood, which causes the blood to become diluted or 'too watery.' This can happen from drinking excessive fluids, certain medications, kidney disease, or hormonal problems. Symptoms may include confusion, headaches, nausea, weakness, or in severe cases, seizures or loss of consciousness.",
    "whoUses": "Emergency medicine physicians, nephrologists (kidney specialists), and critical care doctors commonly diagnose and treat this condition in hospital settings. It frequently appears in hospital bills and ICU care records, though it's less common on routine outpatient insurance statements unless the patient has chronic kidney disease or is on specific medications that cause it.",
